Hi All,

This is the PCI motherboards for OS/2 list.  The 'General Comments'
section has been extensively revised this week, to reflect new
information and understanding of problems with various PCI motherboards
and chipsets. Specifically, new and (hopefully) accurate information has
been added to fully detail the three (yes, three) problems with the
Intel Plato motherboards (two of which have now been fixed).  As usual,
'*' indicates the recommended motherboards, and '**' indicates that I
would choose this motherboard myself when picking a PCI motherboard for
my own PCI system.

Also as usual, please feel free to correct any continuing misconceptions
I might have, to insist that I should recommend a motherboard I don't,
or to add a new motherboard/bit of information to what's here already.
Your contributions and/or corrections are always welcome and certainly
appreciated.  Please, when reporting problems or successes, try to be as
detailed as possible in your hardware descriptions.  BIOS rev. numbers
are especially useful.

Known PCI Motherboard Problems and Workarounds:
-----------------------------------------------

Boards using Saturn I (rev. 1 and 2):

The German Computer Magazine C't indicates that the 486 PCI "Saturn"
chipsets (revision 02 and earlier) had a problem with PCI to CPU burst
mode, and with cache integrity during high-speed bus operations (like
SCSI disk reads/writes).

If you have a board with this chipset, and you want to run SCSI, your
best bet is to switch off the external cache (via the CMOS setup
options).  You could also try disabling synchronous negotiation with
(what is usually) the /!SN switch for your SCSI adapter driver.  Either
way, there's a performance penalty to be paid, unfortunately.

If you're in the market for a board, do _not_ buy a board with the
Saturn-I rev. 2 chipset.  Ask (before you buy) to see if you have the
Saturn-II rev. 4 chipset on the board.  A good visual way to do this is
to check the last two letters on the chips themselves.  The presence of
a chip with the letters 'ZX' indicates you have Saturn II rev. 4.  See
below for a method using DOS debug.

Intel Plato 90 MHz motherboards:

There are three problems with these motherboards.  Each will be taken in
turn:

1) The PCTech RZ1000 chip used for IDE operations on the PCI bus has a
   bug which causes disk write errors once in approximately every 50,000
   operations.

Workarounds (best performance solution first):

a) Get a PCI IDE controller like the BusLogic BT-910 and use it
   instead.

b) Use the ISA IDE port (which is run by a different chip) for your IDE
   drives.

c) Use the PCI IDE port in combination with the IBMINT13.I13 driver.
   Make sure you have BIOS 1.00.10.AX1 (available from the Intel BBS) if
   you choose this (least desirable) route.


2) The SMC I/O chip may cause lockups in DOS/Win if the serial ports
   (COM1 and COM2) are not properly flushed prior to use.  OS/2 is
   apparently unaffected by this problem.

Workarounds (best solution first):

a) New boards have a corrected version of the SMC chip on it.  To see if
   your board has this chip, check the last two letters in it; they
   should be 'GT'.  I have the 'GT' chip in my board, which was received
   in early Sept. of '94.

b) Intel has a software fix (for DOS/Win) for older boards with this
   chip.


3) The Neptune LBX chipset has a problem with buffered writes which only
   affects busmastering PCI devices (i.e. SCSI).  It shows up as a data
   integrity problem during write operations.

Workarounds (best solution first):

a) New boards (shipped by Intel to vendors in August '94 and later) have
   a proper hardware fix for this problem.  This can be identified by
   using debug in DOS (the Neptune chipset shows up as rev. 11), or by
   looking at the PBA# on the system board (wherever that is).  A board
   with the proper chip has the extension '-205' at the end of the PBA#.

b) If you have an older board, get rev. 1.00.10.AX1 of the BIOS (from
   the Intel BBS) and apply it.  This will switch off posted buffered
   writes in the chipset and apparently fix, or at least reduce the
   incidence of, the problem, if rev. A0 of the chip is detected.  Newer
   chipsets will have buffered writes left on.


