 Intel                 Pentium**     The 66 and 90 MHz Pentium boards
                                     have passed OS/2 certification.
These boards are, therefore, highly recommended.  The 60 MHz board has
been reported to be problematic with SCSI, though Adaptec now seems to
think their AHA-2940 SCSI controller should work with it, as do BusLogic
and QLogic (I have had reports of success with the QLogic controller but
not with the Adaptec or BusLogic).  The 60 and 66 MHz boards use the
Mercury chipset, while the 90 MHz board uses the Neptune chipset.  All
the boards come with 256 kB of L2 cache, and can accommodate up to 128
MB (4x32 MB 72-pin SIMMs) of RAM.  All boards have the NCR SCSI BIOS
built in, and have IDE (for ISA and PCI) and I/O ports on the board. The
boards can be run with 4 ISA/3 PCI or 5 ISA/2 PCI slots.  Note:  If you
are using this board with an ATI card (which uses part of COM4's address
space), make sure that you turn off intelligent remapping of the serial
ports, lest COM2 should get remapped to COM4 and cause a conflict
(though the ATI install program picks this up).  Also note:  My MB came
with non-standard BIOS settings which caused difficulties for my tape
backup program.  It may be in your interest, therefore, to go through
your BIOS settings (standard and advanced both) with the motherboard
manual in hand and reset these.  Of special interest is the 'Guaranteed
Access Timing' (GAT) mode, which must be set to 'off' for BackMaster 1.1
to work.  GAT has been turned off and removed from the menu optioms in
BIOS 1.00.10.AX1

